Button.!doc:
Create a new `Button` object. A Button is a special type of Sprite that is set-up to handle Pointer events automatically. The four states a Button responds to are:

* 'Over' - when the Pointer moves over the Button. This is also commonly known as 'hover'.
* 'Out' - when the Pointer that was previously over the Button moves out of it.
* 'Down' - when the Pointer is pressed down on the Button. I.e. touched on a touch enabled device or clicked with the mouse.
* 'Up' - when the Pointer that was pressed down on the Button is released again.

You can set a unique texture frame and Sound for any of these states.

alive.!doc: A useful boolean to control if the Image is alive or dead (in terms of your gameplay, it doesn't effect rendering).

angle.!doc: The angle of this Image in degrees.

animations.!doc: This manages animations of the sprite. You can modify animations through it (see Phaser.AnimationManager)

autoCull.!doc: A flag indicating if the Image should be automatically camera culled or not.

cameraOffset.!doc: If this object is fixedToCamera then this stores the x/y offset that its drawn at, from the top-left of the camera view.

cropRect.!doc: The Rectangle used to crop the texture. Set this via Sprite.crop. Any time you modify this property directly you must call Sprite.updateCrop.

deltaX.!doc: The delta value. Positive if the motion was to the right, negative if to the left.

deltaY.!doc: The delta value. Positive if the motion was downwards, negative if upwards.

Events.!doc:
The Events component is a collection of events fired by the parent game object.

For example to tell when a Sprite has been added to a new group:

`sprite.events.onAddedToGroup.add(yourFunction, this);`

Where `yourFunction` is the function you want called when this event occurs.

Note that the Input related events only exist if the Sprite has had `inputEnabled` set to `true`.

onAddedToGroup.!doc: This signal is dispatched when the parent is added to a new Group.

onAnimationComplete.!doc: This signal is dispatched when the parent has an animation that finishes playing.

onAnimationLoop.!doc: This signal is dispatched when the parent has an animation that loops playback.

onAnimationStart.!doc: This signal is dispatched when the parent has an animation that is played.

onDestroy.!doc: This signal is dispatched when the parent is destoyed.

onDragStart.!doc: This signal is dispatched if the parent is inputEnabled and receives a drag start event from a Pointer.

onDragStop.!doc: This signal is dispatched if the parent is inputEnabled and receives a drag stop event from a Pointer.

onEnterBounds.!doc: This signal is dispatched when the parent returns within the world bounds (only if Sprite.checkWorldBounds is true).

The Gamepad class handles looking after gamepad input for your game.
Remember to call gamepad.start(); expecting input!

HTML5 GAMEPAD API SUPPORT IS AT AN EXPERIMENTAL STAGE!
At moment of writing this (end of 2013) only Chrome supports parts of it out of the box. Firefox supports it
via prefs flags (about:config, search gamepad). The browsers map the same controllers differently.
This class has constants for Windows 7 Chrome mapping of XBOX 360 controller.

justPressedRate.!doc: The number of milliseconds below which the Pointer is considered justPressed.

justReleasedRate.!doc: The number of milliseconds below which the Pointer is considered justReleased .

maxPointers.!doc: The maximum number of Pointers allowed to be active at any one time. For lots of games it's useful to set this to 1.

minPriorityID.!doc: You can tell all Pointers to ignore any object with a priorityID lower than the minPriorityID. Useful when stacking UI layers. Set to zero to disable.

mousePointer.!doc: The mouse has its own unique Phaser.Pointer object which you can use if making a desktop specific game.

moveCallback.!doc: An optional callback that will be fired every time the activePointer receives a move event from the DOM. Set to null to disable.

moveCallbackContext.!doc: The context in which the moveCallback will be sent. Defaults to Phaser.Input but can be set to any valid JS object.

moveCallbacks.!doc: An array of callbacks that will be fired every time the activePointer receives a move event from the DOM.

multiInputOverride.!doc: Controls the expected behaviour when using a mouse and touch together on a multi-input device.

onDown.!doc: A Signal that is dispatched each time a pointer is pressed down.

onHold.!doc: A Signal that is dispatched each time a pointer is held down.

onTap.!doc: A Signal that is dispatched each time a pointer is tapped.

onUp.!doc: A Signal that is dispatched each time a pointer is released.

pollLocked.!doc: True if the Input is currently poll rate locked.

pollRate.!doc: How often should the input pointers be checked for updates? A value of 0 means every single frame (60fps); a value of 1 means every other frame (30fps) and so on.

position.!doc: A point object representing the current position of the Pointer.

recordRate.!doc: The rate in milliseconds at which the Pointer objects should update their tracking history.

resetLocked.!doc: If the Input Manager has been reset locked then all calls made to InputManager.reset, such as from a State change, are ignored.

scale.!doc: The scale by which all input coordinates are multiplied; calculated by the ScaleManager. In an un-scaled game the values will be x = 1 and y = 1.

speed.!doc: A point object representing the speed of the Pointer. Only really useful in single Pointer games; otherwise see the Pointer objects directly.

tapRate.!doc: The number of milliseconds that the Pointer has to be pressed down and then released to be considered a tap or click.

totalActivePointers.!doc: The total number of active Pointers.

totalInactivePointers.!doc: The total number of inactive Pointers.

worldX.!doc: The world X coordinate of the most recently active pointer.

worldY.!doc: The world Y coordinate of the most recently active pointer.

x.!doc: The X coordinate of the most recently active pointer.

y.!doc: The Y coordinate of the most recently active pointer.

hitTest.!type: fn(displayObject: PIXI.DisplayObject, pointer: Phaser.Pointer, localPoint: Phaser.Point)

InputHandler.!doc: The Input Handler is bound to a specific Sprite and is responsible for managing all Input events on that Sprite.

allowHorizontalDrag.!doc: Controls if the Sprite is allowed to be dragged horizontally.

allowVerticalDrag.!doc: Controls if the Sprite is allowed to be dragged vertically.

boundsRect.!doc: A region of the game world within which the sprite is restricted during drag.

boundsSprite.!doc: A Sprite the bounds of which this sprite is restricted during drag.

bringToTop.!doc: If true when this Sprite is clicked or dragged it will automatically be bought to the top of the Group it is within.

draggable.!doc: Is this sprite allowed to be dragged by the mouse? true = yes, false = no

enabled.!doc: If enabled the Input Handler will process input requests and monitor pointer activity.

game.!doc: A reference to the currently running game.

isDragged.!doc: true if the Sprite is being currently dragged.

pixelPerfectAlpha.!doc: The alpha tolerance threshold. If the alpha value of the pixel matches or is above this value, it's considered a hit.

pixelPerfectClick.!doc: Use a pixel perfect check when testing for clicks or touches on the Sprite.

pixelPerfectOver.!doc: Use a pixel perfect check when testing for pointer over.

scaleLayer.!doc: EXPERIMENTAL: Please do not use this property unless you know what it does. Likely to change in the future.

snapOffset.!doc: A Point object that contains by how far the Sprite snap is offset.

snapOffsetX.!doc: This defines the top-left X coordinate of the snap grid.

snapOffsetY.!doc: This defines the top-left Y coordinate of the snap grid..

snapOnDrag.!doc: When the Sprite is dragged this controls if the center of the Sprite will snap to the pointer on drag or not.

snapOnRelease.!doc: When the Sprite is dragged this controls if the Sprite will be snapped on release.

snapX.!doc: When a Sprite has snapping enabled this holds the width of the snap grid.

snapY.!doc: When a Sprite has snapping enabled this holds the height of the snap grid.

sprite.!doc: The Sprite object to which this Input Handler belongs.

useHandCursor.!doc: On a desktop browser you can set the 'hand' cursor to appear when moving over the Sprite.

checkPixel.!type: fn(x: number, y: number, pointer?: Phaser.Pointer) -> bool

enableSnap.!type: fn(snapX: number, snapY: number, onDrag?: bool, onRelease?: boolean, snapOffsetX?: number, snapOffsetX?: number)

Key.!doc: If you need more fine-grained control over the handling of specific keys you can create and use Phaser.Key objects.

altKey.!doc: The down state of the ALT key, if pressed at the same time as this key.

ctrlKey.!doc: The down state of the CTRL key, if pressed at the same time as this key.

duration.!doc: The number of milliseconds this key has been held down for.

enabled.!doc: An enabled key processes its update and dispatches events. You can toggle this at run-time to disable a key without deleting it.

event.!doc: Stores the most recent DOM event.

game.!doc: A reference to the currently running game.

onDown.!doc: This Signal is dispatched every time this Key is pressed down. It is only dispatched once (until the key is released again).

onHoldCallback.!doc: A callback that is called while this Key is held down. Warning: Depending on refresh rate that could be 60+ times per second.

onHoldContext.!doc: The context under which the onHoldCallback will be called.

onUp.!doc: This Signal is dispatched every time this Key is pressed down. It is only dispatched once (until the key is released again).

repeats.!doc: If a key is held down this holds down the number of times the key has 'repeated'.

shiftKey.!doc: The down state of the SHIFT key, if pressed at the same time as this key.

timeDown.!doc: The timestamp when the key was last pressed down. This is based on Game.time.now.

timeUp.!doc: The timestamp when the key was last released. This is based on Game.time.now.

Keyboard.!doc:
The Keyboard class handles looking after keyboard input for your game.
It will recognise and respond to key presses and dispatch the required events.
Please be aware that lots of keyboards are unable to process certain combinations of keys due to hardware
limitations known as ghosting. Full details here: http://www.html5gamedevs.com/topic/4876-impossible-to-use-more-than-2-keyboard-input-buttons-at-the-same-time/

callbackContext.!doc: The context under which the callbacks are run.

disabled.!doc: The disabled state of the Keyboard.

event.!doc: The most recent DOM event from keydown or keyup. This is updated every time a new key is pressed or released.

game.!doc: Local reference to game.

lastChar.!doc: The string value of the most recently pressed key.

onDownCallback.!doc: This callback is invoked every time a key is pressed down, including key repeats when a key is held down.

onPressCallback.!doc: This callback is invoked every time a DOM onkeypress event is raised, which is only for printable keys.

onUpCallback.!doc: This callback is invoked every time a key is released.

pressEvent.!doc: The most recent DOM event from keypress.

Loader.!doc:
The Loader handles loading all external content such as Images, Sounds, Texture Atlases and data files.
It uses a combination of Image() loading and xhr and provides progress and completion callbacks.

crossOrigin.!doc: The crossOrigin value applied to loaded images. Very often this needs to be set to 'anonymous'.

game.!doc: Local reference to game.

hasLoaded.!doc: True if all assets in the queue have finished loading.

isLoading.!doc: True if the Loader is in the process of loading the queue.

onFileComplete.!doc: This event is dispatched when a file completes loading successfully.

onFileError.!doc: This event is dispatched when a file errors as a result of the load request.

onFileStart.!doc: This event is dispatched immediately before a file starts loading. It's possible the file may still error (404, etc) after this event is sent.

onLoadComplete.!doc: This event is dispatched when the final file in the load queue has either loaded or failed.

onLoadStart.!doc: This event is dispatched when the loading process starts, before the first file has been requested.

onPackComplete.!doc: This event is dispatched when an asset pack has either loaded or failed.

progress.!doc: The rounded load progress percentage value (from 0 to 100)

progressFloat.!doc: The non-rounded load progress value (from 0.0 to 100.0)

useXDomainRequest.!doc: If true and if the browser supports XDomainRequest, it will be used in preference for xhr when loading json files. It is enabled automatically if the browser is IE9, but you can disable it as required.

Mouse.!doc:
Phaser.Mouse is responsible for handling all aspects of mouse interaction with the browser.
It captures and processes mouse events that happen on the game canvas object. It also adds a single `mouseup` listener to `window` which
is used to capture the mouse being released when not over the game.

button-.!doc: The type of click, either: Phaser.Mouse.NO_BUTTON, Phaser.Mouse.LEFT_BUTTON, Phaser.Mouse.MIDDLE_BUTTON or Phaser.Mouse.RIGHT_BUTTON.

callbackContext.!doc: The context under which callbacks are called.

capture.!doc: If true the DOM mouse events will have event.preventDefault applied to them, if false they will propogate fully.

disabled.!doc: You can disable all Input by setting disabled = true. While set all new input related events will be ignored.

event.!doc: The browser mouse DOM event. Will be set to null if no mouse event has ever been received.

game.!doc: A reference to the currently running game.

locked.!doc: If the mouse has been Pointer Locked successfully this will be set to true.

mouseDownCallback.!doc: A callback that can be fired when the mouse is pressed down.

mouseMoveCallback.!doc: A callback that can be fired when the mouse is moved while pressed down.

mouseOutCallback.!doc: A callback that can be fired when the mouse is no longer over the game canvas.

mouseOverCallback.!doc: A callback that can be fired when the mouse enters the game canvas (usually after a mouseout).

mouseUpCallback.!doc: A callback that can be fired when the mouse is released from a pressed down state.

mouseWheelCallback.!doc: A callback that can be fired when the mousewheel is used.

pointerLock.!doc: This event is dispatched when the browser enters or leaves pointer lock state.

stopOnGameOut.!doc: If true Pointer.stop will be called if the mouse leaves the game canvas.

wheelDelta.!doc: The direction of the mousewheel usage 1 for up -1 for down

Particle.!doc: Create a new `Particle` object. Particles are extended Sprites that are emitted by a particle emitter such as Phaser.Particles.Arcade.Emitter.

alive.!doc: A useful boolean to control if the Sprite is alive or dead (in terms of your gameplay, it doesn't effect rendering). Also linked to Sprite.health and Sprite.damage.

angle.!doc: The angle of this Sprite in degrees.

animations.!doc: This manages animations of the sprite. You can modify animations through it (see Phaser.AnimationManager)

autoCull.!doc: A flag indicating if the Sprite should be automatically camera culled or not.

cameraOffset.!doc: If this object is fixedToCamera then this stores the x/y offset that its drawn at, from the top-left of the camera view.

cropRect.!doc: The Rectangle used to crop the texture. Set this via Sprite.crop. Any time you modify this property directly you must call Sprite.updateCrop.

debug.!doc: Handy flag to use with Game.enableStep

deltaX.!doc: The delta value. Positive if the motion was to the right, negative if to the left.

deltaY.!doc: The delta value. Positive if the motion was downwards, negative if upwards.

destroyPhase.!doc: True if this object is currently being destroyed.

events.!doc: The Events you can subscribe to that are dispatched when certain things happen on this Sprite or its components.

exists.!doc: If the Sprite is processed by the core game update and physics.

fixedToCamera.!doc: Set to true to fix this Sprite to the Camera at its current world coordinates.

frame.!doc: Gets or sets the current frame index and updates the Texture Cache for display.

frameName.!doc: Gets or sets the current frame name and updates the Texture Cache for display.

game.!doc: A reference to the currently running Game.

health.!doc: Health value. Used in combination with damage() to allow for quick killing of Sprites.

inCamera.!doc: True if the Sprite bounds is within the game camera, even if only partially. Otherwise false if fully outside of it.

inWorld.!doc: True if the Sprite bounds is within the game world, even if only partially. Otherwise false if fully outside of it.

input.!doc: The Input Handler for this object. Needs to be enabled with image.inputEnabled = true before you can use it.

inputEnabled.!doc: Set to true to allow this object to receive input events.

key.!doc: This is the image or texture used by the Sprite during rendering. It can be a string which is a reference to the Cache entry, or an instance of a RenderTexture, BitmapData or PIXI.Texture.

lifespan.!doc: The lifespan of the Sprite (in ms) before it will be killed.

name.!doc: The user defined name given to this Sprite.

outOfBoundsKill.!doc: If true Sprite.kill is called as soon as Sprite.inWorld returns false, as long as Sprite.checkWorldBounds is true.

renderOrderID.!doc: The render order ID, reset every frame.

smoothed.!doc: Set to true to smooth the texture of this Sprite, or false to disable smoothing (great for pixel art)

type.!doc: The const type of this object.

world.!doc: The world coordinates of this Sprite. This differs from the x/y coordinates which are relative to the Sprites container.

x.!doc: The position of the Sprite on the x axis relative to the local coordinates of the parent.

y.!doc: The position of the Sprite on the y axis relative to the local coordinates of the parent.

z.!doc: The z-depth value of this object within its Group (remember the World is a Group as well). No two objects in a Group can have the same z value.

Emitter.!doc:
Emitter is a lightweight particle emitter that uses Arcade Physics.
It can be used for one-time explosions or for continuous effects like rain and fire.
All it really does is launch Particle objects out at set intervals, and fixes their positions and velocities accordingly.

alive.!doc: The alive property is useful for Groups that are children of other Groups and need to be included/excluded in checks like forEachAlive.

alphaData.!doc: An array of the calculated alpha easing data applied to particles with alphaRates > 0.

angle.!doc: The angle of rotation given in degrees, where 0 degrees = to the right.

angularDrag.!doc: The angular drag component of particles launched from the emitter if they are rotating.

area.!doc: The area of the emitter. Particles can be randomly generated from anywhere within this rectangle.

autoAlpha.!doc: When a new Particle is emitted this controls if it will automatically change alpha. Use Emitter.setAlpha to configure.

autoScale.!doc: When a new Particle is emitted this controls if it will automatically scale in size. Use Emitter.setScale to configure.

blendMode.!doc: The blendMode as set on the particle when emitted from the Emitter. Defaults to NORMAL. Needs browser capable of supporting canvas blend-modes (most not available in WebGL)

bottom.!doc: Gets the bottom position of the Emitter.

bounce.!doc: How much each particle should bounce on each axis. 1 = full bounce, 0 = no bounce.

cameraOffset.!doc: If this object is fixedToCamera then this stores the x/y offset that its drawn at, from the top-left of the camera view.

cursor.!doc: The current display object that the Group cursor is pointing to.

enableBody.!doc: If true all Sprites created by, or added to this Group, will have a physics body enabled on them. Change the body type with `Group.physicsBodyType`.

enableBodyDebug.!doc: If true when a physics body is created (via Group.enableBody) it will create a physics debug object as well. Only works for P2 bodies.

exists.!doc: If exists is true the Group is updated, otherwise it is skipped.

fixedToCamera.!doc: Set to true to fix this Group to the Camera at its current world coordinates.

frequency.!doc: How often a particle is emitted in ms (if emitter is started with Explode === false).

game.!doc: A reference to the currently running Game.

gravity.!doc: Sets the `body.gravity.y` of each particle sprite to this value on launch.

height.!doc: Gets or sets the height of the Emitter. This is the region in which a particle can be emitted.

ignoreDestroy.!doc: A Group with `ignoreDestroy` set to `true` ignores all calls to its `destroy` method.

left.!doc: Gets the left position of the Emitter.

length.!doc: The total number of children in this Group, regardless of their exists/alive status.

lifespan.!doc: How long each particle lives once it is emitted in ms. Default is 2 seconds. Set lifespan to 'zero' for particles to live forever.

maxParticleAlpha.!doc: The maximum possible alpha value of a particle.

maxParticleScale.!doc: The maximum possible scale of a particle. This is applied to the X and Y axis. If you need to control each axis see maxParticleScaleX.

maxParticleSpeed.!doc: The maximum possible velocity of a particle.

maxParticles.!doc: The total number of particles in this emitter.

maxRotation.!doc: The maximum possible angular velocity of a particle.

minParticleAlpha.!doc: The minimum possible alpha value of a particle.

minParticleScale.!doc: The minimum possible scale of a particle. This is applied to the X and Y axis. If you need to control each axis see minParticleScaleX.

minParticleSpeed.!doc: The minimum possible velocity of a particle.

minRotation.!doc: The minimum possible angular velocity of a particle.

name.!doc: A handy string name for this emitter. Can be set to anything.

on.!doc: Determines whether the emitter is currently emitting particles. It is totally safe to directly toggle this.

onDestroy.!doc: This signal is dispatched when the parent is destoyed.

particleAnchor.!doc: When a particle is created its anchor will be set to match this Point object (defaults to x/y: 0.5 to aid in rotation)

particleBringToTop.!doc: If this is `true` then when the Particle is emitted it will be bought to the top of the Emitters display list.

particleClass.!doc: For emitting your own particle class types. They must extend Phaser.Particle.

particleDrag.!doc: The X and Y drag component of particles launched from the emitter.

particleSendToBack.!doc: If this is `true` then when the Particle is emitted it will be sent to the back of the Emitters display list.

physicsBodyType.!doc: If Group.enableBody is true this is the type of physics body that is created on new Sprites. Phaser.Physics.ARCADE, Phaser.Physics.P2, Phaser.Physics.NINJA, etc.

pivot.!doc: The pivot point of the Group container.

right.!doc: Gets the right position of the Emitter.

rotation.!doc: The angle of rotation given in radians.

scale.!doc: The scale of the Group container.

scaleData.!doc: An array of the calculated scale easing data applied to particles with scaleRates > 0.

top.!doc: Gets the top position of the Emitter.

total.!doc: The total number of children in this Group who have a state of exists = true.

visible.!doc: The visible state of the Group. Non-visible Groups and all of their children are not rendered.

width.!doc: Gets or sets the width of the Emitter. This is the region in which a particle can be emitted.

x.!doc: Gets or sets the x position of the Emitter.

y.!doc: Gets or sets the y position of the Emitter.

z.!doc: The z-depth value of this object within its Group (remember the World is a Group as well). No two objects in a Group can have the same z value.

Ninja.!doc:
Ninja Physics. The Ninja Physics system was created in Flash by Metanet Software and ported to JavaScript by Richard Davey.

It allows for AABB and Circle to Tile collision. Tiles can be any of 34 different types, including slopes, convex and concave shapes.

It does what it does very well, but is ripe for expansion and optimisation. Here are some features that I'd love to see the community add:

* AABB to AABB collision
* AABB to Circle collision
* AABB and Circle 'immovable' property support
* n-way collision, so an AABB/Circle could pass through a tile from below and land upon it.
* QuadTree or spatial grid for faster Body vs. Tile Group look-ups.
* Optimise the internal vector math and reduce the quantity of temporary vars created.
* Expand Gravity and Bounce to allow for separate x/y axis values.
* Support Bodies linked to Sprites that don't have anchor set to 0.5

Feel free to attempt any of the above and submit a Pull Request with your code! Be sure to include test cases proving they work.

Body.!doc:
The Physics Body is typically linked to a single Sprite and defines properties that determine how the physics body is simulated.
These properties affect how the body reacts to forces, what forces it generates on itself (to simulate friction), and how it reacts to collisions in the scene.
In most cases, the properties are used to simulate physical effects. Each body also has its own property values that determine exactly how it reacts to forces and collisions in the scene.
By default a single Rectangle shape is added to the Body that matches the dimensions of the parent Sprite. See addShape, removeShape, clearShapes to add extra shapes around the Body.
Note: When bound to a Sprite to avoid single-pixel jitters on mobile devices we strongly recommend using Sprite sizes that are even on both axis, i.e. 128x128 not 127x127.
Note: When a game object is given a P2 body it has its anchor x/y set to 0.5, so it becomes centered.

Physics.!doc:
The Physics Manager is responsible for looking after all of the running physics systems.
Phaser supports 3 physics systems: Arcade Physics, P2 and Ninja Physics (with Box2D and Chipmunk in development)
Game Objects can belong to only 1 physics system, but you can have multiple systems active in a single game.

For example you could have P2 managing a polygon-built terrain landscape that an vehicle drives over, while it could be firing bullets that use the
faster (due to being much simpler) Arcade Physics system.

A Retro Font is similar to a BitmapFont, in that it uses a texture to render the text. However unlike a BitmapFont every character in a RetroFont
is the same size. This makes it similar to a sprite sheet. You typically find font sheets like this from old 8/16-bit games and demos.

A Rope is a Sprite that has a repeating texture. The texture can be scrolled and scaled and will automatically wrap on the edges as it does so.
Please note that Ropes, as with normal Sprites, have no input handler or physics bodies by default. Both need enabling.

Sprite.!doc:
Sprites are the lifeblood of your game, used for nearly everything visual.

At its most basic a Sprite consists of a set of coordinates and a texture that is rendered to the canvas.
They also contain additional properties allowing for physics motion (via Sprite.body), input handling (via Sprite.input),
events (via Sprite.events), animation (via Sprite.animations), camera culling and more. Please see the Examples for use cases.

alive.!doc: A useful boolean to control if the Sprite is alive or dead (in terms of your gameplay, it doesn't effect rendering). Also linked to Sprite.health and Sprite.damage.

angle.!doc: The angle of this Sprite in degrees.

animations.!doc: This manages animations of the sprite. You can modify animations through it (see Phaser.AnimationManager)

autoCull.!doc: A flag indicating if the Sprite should be automatically camera culled or not.

cameraOffset.!doc: If this object is fixedToCamera then this stores the x/y offset that its drawn at, from the top-left of the camera view.

cropRect.!doc: The Rectangle used to crop the texture. Set this via Sprite.crop. Any time you modify this property directly you must call Sprite.updateCrop.

debug.!doc: Handy flag to use with Game.enableStep

deltaX.!doc: The delta value. Positive if the motion was to the right, negative if to the left.

deltaY.!doc: The delta value. Positive if the motion was downwards, negative if upwards.

destroyPhase.!doc: True if this object is currently being destroyed.

events.!doc: The Events you can subscribe to that are dispatched when certain things happen on this Sprite or its components.

exists.!doc: If the Sprite is processed by the core game update and physics.

fixedToCamera.!doc: Set to true to fix this Sprite to the Camera at its current world coordinates.

frame.!doc: Gets or sets the current frame index and updates the Texture Cache for display.

frameName.!doc: Gets or sets the current frame name and updates the Texture Cache for display.

SpriteBatch.!doc:
The SpriteBatch class is a really fast version of the DisplayObjectContainer built purely for speed, so use when you need a lot of sprites or particles.
It's worth mentioning that by default sprite batches are used through-out the renderer, so you only really need to use a SpriteBatch if you have over
1000 sprites that all share the same texture (or texture atlas). It's also useful if running in Canvas mode and you have a lot of un-rotated or un-scaled
Sprites as it skips all of the Canvas setTransform calls, which helps performance, especially on mobile devices.

angle.!doc: The angle of rotation given in degrees, where 0 degrees = to the right.

State.!doc:
This is a base State class which can be extended if you are creating your own game.
It provides quick access to common functions such as the camera, cache, input, match, sound and more.

math.!doc: A reference to Math class with lots of helpful functions.

particles.!doc: The Particle Manager. It is called during the core gameloop and updates any Particle Emitters it has created.

physics.!doc: A reference to the physics manager which looks after the different physics systems available within Phaser.

rnd.!doc: A reference to the seeded and repeatable random data generator.

scale.!doc: A reference to the Scale Manager which controls the way the game scales on different displays.

sound.!doc: A reference to the Sound Manager which can create, play and stop sounds, as well as adjust global volume.

time.!doc: A reference to the game clock and timed events system.

tweens.!doc: A reference to the tween manager.

world.!doc: A reference to the game world. All objects live in the Game World and its size is not bound by the display resolution.

Text.!doc:
Create a new `Text` object. This uses a local hidden Canvas object and renders the type into it. It then makes a texture from this for renderning to the view.
Because of this you can only display fonts that are currently loaded and available to the browser. It won't load the fonts for you.
Here is a compatibility table showing the available default fonts across different mobile browsers: http://www.jordanm.co.uk/tinytype

align.!doc: Alignment for multiline text ('left', 'center' or 'right'), does not affect single line text.

angle.!doc: Gets or sets the angle of rotation in degrees.

cameraOffset.!doc: If this object is fixedToCamera then this stores the x/y offset that its drawn at, from the top-left of the camera view.

colors.!doc: An array of the color values as specified by `Text.addColor`.

destroyPhase.!doc: True if this object is currently being destroyed.

events.!doc: The Events you can subscribe to that are dispatched when certain things happen on this Sprite or its components.

exists.!doc: If exists = false then the Text isn't updated by the core game loop.

input.!doc: The Input Handler for this object. Needs to be enabled with image.inputEnabled = true before you can use it.

inputEnabled.!doc: Set to true to allow this object to receive input events.

lineSpacing.!doc: Additional spacing (in pixels) between each line of text if multi-line.

name.!doc: The user defined name given to this object.

shadowBlur.!doc: The shadowBlur value. Make the shadow softer by applying a Gaussian blur to it. A number from 0 (no blur) up to approx. 10 (depending on scene).

shadowColor.!doc: The color of the shadow, as given in CSS rgba format. Set the alpha component to 0 to disable the shadow.

shadowOffsetX.!doc: The shadowOffsetX value in pixels. This is how far offset horizontally the shadow effect will be.

shadowOffsetY.!doc: The shadowOffsetY value in pixels. This is how far offset vertically the shadow effect will be.

stroke.!doc: A canvas fillstyle that will be used on the text stroke eg 'blue', '#FCFF00'.

strokeThickness.!doc: A number that represents the thickness of the stroke. Default is 0 (no stroke)

TileSprite.!doc:
A TileSprite is a Sprite that has a repeating texture. The texture can be scrolled and scaled and will automatically wrap on the edges as it does so.
Please note that TileSprites, as with normal Sprites, have no input handler or physics bodies by default. Both need enabling.

alive.!doc: A useful boolean to control if the TileSprite is alive or dead (in terms of your gameplay, it doesn't effect rendering).

angle.!doc: The angle of this Sprite in degrees.

animations.!doc: This manages animations of the sprite. You can modify animations through it (see Phaser.AnimationManager)

autoCull.!doc: A flag indicating if the Sprite should be automatically camera culled or not.

cameraOffset.!doc: If this object is fixedToCamera then this stores the x/y offset that its drawn at, from the top-left of the camera view.

destroyPhase.!doc: True if this object is currently being destroyed.

events.!doc: The Events you can subscribe to that are dispatched when certain things happen on this Sprite or its components.

fixedToCamera.!doc: Set to true to fix this TileSprite to the Camera at its current world coordinates.

type.!doc: The const type of this object.

y.!doc: The position of the TileSprite on the y axis relative to the local coordinates of the parent.

Tilemap.!doc:
Creates a new Phaser.Tilemap object. The map can either be populated with data from a Tiled JSON file or from a CSV file.
To do this pass the Cache key as the first parameter. When using Tiled data you need only provide the key.
When using CSV data you must provide the key and the tileWidth and tileHeight parameters.
If creating a blank tilemap to be populated later, you can either specify no parameters at all and then use `Tilemap.create` or pass the map and tile dimensions here.
Note that all Tilemaps use a base tile size to calculate dimensions from, but that a TilemapLayer may have its own unique tile size that overrides it.
A Tile map is rendered to the display using a TilemapLayer. It is not added to the display list directly itself.
A map may have multiple layers. You can perform operations on the map data such as copying, pasting, filling and shuffling the tiles around.

collision.!doc: An array of collision data (polylines, etc).

heightInPixels.!doc: The height of the map in pixels based on height * tileHeight.

properties.!doc: Map specific properties as specified in Tiled.

tileHeight.!doc: The base height of the tiles in the map (in pixels).

tileWidth.!doc: The base width of the tiles in the map (in pixels).

width.!doc: The width of the map (in tiles).

widthInPixels.!doc: The width of the map in pixels based on width * tileWidth.

Time.!doc:
This is the core internal game clock.
It manages the elapsed time and calculation of elapsed values, used for game object motion and tweens.

advancedTiming.!doc: If true Phaser.Time will perform advanced profiling including the fps rate, fps min/max and msMin and msMax.

deltaCap.!doc: If you need to cap the delta timer, set the value here. For 60fps the delta should be 0.016, so try variances just above this.

events.!doc: This is a Phaser.Timer object bound to the master clock to which you can add timed events.

fpsMax.!doc: The highest rate the fps has reached (usually no higher than 60fps). Only calculated if Time.advancedTiming is true.

fpsMin.!doc: The lowest rate the fps has dropped to. Only calculated if Time.advancedTiming is true.

frames.!doc: The number of frames record in the last second. Only calculated if Time.advancedTiming is true.

game.!doc: Local reference to game.

lastTime.!doc: Internal value used by timeToCall as part of the setTimeout loop

msMax.!doc: The maximum amount of time the game has taken between two frames. Only calculated if Time.advancedTiming is true.

msMin.!doc: The minimum amount of time the game has taken between two frames. Only calculated if Time.advancedTiming is true.

pauseDuration.!doc: Records how long the game was paused for in miliseconds.

physicsElapsed.!doc: The elapsed time calculated for the physics motion updates. In a stable 60fps system this will be 0.016 every frame.

timeCap.!doc: If the difference in time between two frame updates exceeds this value, the frame time is reset to avoid huge elapsed counts.

timeToCall.!doc: The value that setTimeout needs to work out when to next update

Timer.!doc:
A Timer is a way to create small re-usable or disposable objects that do nothing but wait for a specific moment in time, and then dispatch an event.
You can add as many events to a Timer as you like, each with their own delays. A Timer uses milliseconds as its unit of time. There are 1000 ms in 1 second.
So if you want to fire an event every quarter of a second you'd need to set the delay to 250.

autoDestroy.!doc: A Timer that is set to automatically destroy itself will do so after all of its events have been dispatched (assuming no looping events).

duration.!doc: The duration in ms remaining until the next event will occur.

events.!doc: An array holding all of this timers Phaser.TimerEvent objects. Use the methods add, repeat and loop to populate it.

expired.!doc: An expired Timer is one in which all of its events have been dispatched and none are pending.

game.!doc: Local reference to game.

length.!doc: The number of pending events in the queue.

ms.!doc: The duration in milliseconds that this Timer has been running for.

next.!doc: The time at which the next event will occur.

onComplete.!doc: This signal will be dispatched when this Timer has completed, meaning there are no more events in the queue.

paused.!doc: The paused state of the Timer. You can pause the timer by calling Timer.pause() and Timer.resume() or by the game pausing.

running.!doc: True if the Timer is actively running. Do not switch this boolean, if you wish to pause the timer then use Timer.pause() instead.

seconds.!doc: The duration in seconds that this Timer has been running for.

timeCap.!doc: If the difference in time between two frame updates exceeds this value, the event times are reset to avoid catch-up situations.

TimerEvent.!doc:
A TimerEvent is a single event that is processed by a Phaser.Timer.
It consists of a delay, which is a value in milliseconds after which the event will fire.
It can call a specific callback, passing in optional parameters.

callbackContext.!doc: The context in which the callback will be called.

loop.!doc: True if this TimerEvent loops, otherwise false.

repeatCount.!doc: If this TimerEvent repeats it will do so this many times.

tick.!doc: The tick is the next game clock time that this event will fire at.

timer.!doc: The Timer object that this TimerEvent belongs to.

TweenManager.!doc:
Phaser.Game has a single instance of the TweenManager through which all Tween objects are created and updated.
Tweens are hooked into the game clock and pause system, adjusting based on the game state.

TweenManager is based heavily on tween.js by http://soledadpenades.com.
The difference being that tweens belong to a games instance of TweenManager, rather than to a global TWEEN object.
It also has callbacks swapped for Signals and a few issues patched with regard to properties and completion errors.
Please see https://github.com/sole/tween.js for a full list of contributors.

If your game is running in WebGL then Debug will create a Sprite that is placed at the top of the Stage display list and bind a canvas texture

World.!doc:
"This world is but a canvas to our imagination." - Henry David Thoreau

A game has only one world. The world is an abstract place in which all game objects live. It is not bound
by stage limits and can be any size. You look into the world via cameras. All game objects live within
the world at world-based coordinates. By default a world is created the same size as your Stage.

_definedSize.!doc: True if the World has been given a specifically defined size (i.e. from a Tilemap or direct in code) or false if it's just matched to the Game dimensions.

alive.!doc: The alive property is useful for Groups that are children of other Groups and need to be included/excluded in checks like forEachAlive.

bounds.!doc: Bound of this world that objects can not escape from.

centerY.!doc: Gets the Y position corresponding to the center point of the world.

enableBodyDebug.!doc: If true when a physics body is created (via Group.enableBody) it will create a physics debug object as well. Only works for P2 bodies.

fixedToCamera.!doc: Set to true to fix this Group to the Camera at its current world coordinates.

height.!doc: Gets or sets the current height of the game world. The world can never be smaller than the game (canvas) dimensions.

ignoreDestroy.!doc: A Group with `ignoreDestroy` set to `true` ignores all calls to its `destroy` method.

length.!doc: The total number of children in this Group, regardless of their exists/alive status.

pivot.!doc: The pivot point of the Group container.

randomX.!doc: Gets a random integer which is lesser than or equal to the current width of the game world.

randomY.!doc: Gets a random integer which is lesser than or equal to the current height of the game world.

rotation.!doc: The angle of rotation given in radians.

scale.!doc: The scale of the Group container.

total.!doc: The total number of children in this Group who have a state of exists = true.

visible.!doc: The visible state of the Group. Non-visible Groups and all of their children are not rendered.

width.!doc: Gets or sets the current width of the game world. The world can never be smaller than the game (canvas) dimensions.
